illboard.biz |accessdate=2011-10-24}}</ref>\n|38\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Gold|region=Austria}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Platinum|number=3|region=Canada}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Gold|region=France|salesamount=155,700|salesref=<ref name=FRGD>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/CDCertif_O.php?debut=2600 |title=Les Albums Or |publisher=[[SNEP]] |work=infodisc.fr |language=French |accessdate=2011-11-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201212948/http://www.infodisc.fr/CDCertif_O.php?debut=2600 |archivedate=1 February 2014 }}</ref>}}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Platinum|region=Germany}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=album|region=New Zealand|artist=Rod Stewart|title=Vagabond Heart|award=Platinum|id=3464|relyear=1991|accessdate=25 November 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|certyear=1991|award=Platinum|region=Sweden}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Platinum|region=Switzerland|accessdate=17 October 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Platinum|region=United Kingdom}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|title=Vagabond Heart|artist=Rod Stewart|type=album|relyear=1991|award=Platinum|region=United States}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Rod Stewart}}\n\n[[Category:Rod Stewart albums]]\n[[Category:1991 albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bernard Edwards]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Trevor Horn]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Patrick Leonard]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Lenny Waronker]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Richard Perry]]\n", "name_user": "Wyvern Rex.", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vagabond_Heart"}
{"title_page": "Western Carolina University", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Western Carolina University\n| image_name = Western Carolina University seal.png\n| image_size = 150px\n| established = 1889\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| parent = [[University of North Carolina|UNC System]]\n| endowment = $66 million<ref>As of June 30, 2016. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf |title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2016 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2015 to FY 2016 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2017 |access-date=2017-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| chancellor = Kelli R. Brown\n| provost = Richard Starnes (Interim)\n| faculty = 639<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web| title =2007 Fact Book and University Data| publisher =WCU| year =2008| url =http://planning.wcu.edu/2007_Factbook/Employees_Binder.pdf}}</ref>\n| staff = 967<ref name=\"autogenerated3\" />\n| city = [[Cullowhee, North Carolina|Cullowhee]]\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{Coord|35|18|35|N|83|11|00|W|region:US-NC_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| students = 12,167\n| undergrad = 10,469\n| postgrad = 1,698<ref name=\"Fast Facts\">{{cite web|title=Fast Facts|url=http://www.wcu.edu/discover/about/fast-facts.aspx|website=About Western Carolina|publisher=Western Carolina University|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n| campus = Rural/[[Valley]]<br>{{convert|589|acre|km2}}\n| athletics = [[NCAA Division I]] [[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] \u2013 [[Southern Conference|SoCon]]\n| sports = 16 varsity teams\n| nickname = [[Western Carolina Catamounts|Catamounts]]\n| colors = Purple and Gold<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150103082905/http://www.wcu.edu/WebFiles/PDFs/Athleticsbrandstyleguidev4.pdf]</ref><br/>{{color box|#592C88}}&nbsp;{{color box|#C1A875}}\n| website = {{url|www.wcu.edu}}\n| logo = [[File:Western Carolina University Logo.svg|250px]]\n| former_names = Cullowhee Academy (1889\u20131905)<br>Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School (1905\u20131925)<br>Cullowhee State Normal School (1925\u20131929)<br>Western Carolina Teachers College (1929\u20131953)<br>Western Carolina College (1953\u20131967)\n}}\n\n'''Western Carolina University''' ('''WCU''') is a [[public university]] in [[Cullowhee, North Carolina]]. It is part of the [[University of North Carolina]] system.<ref>{{cite web| title =University of North Carolina| date =August 23, 2012| url =http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/INST_WCU.php| access-date =2012-08-23| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20121013145428/http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/INST_WCU.php| archive-date =2012-10-13| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth oldest institution<ref>{{cite web| title =Our 17 Institutions| publisher =The University of North Carolina| date =August 23, 2012| url =http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/index.php| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120107134507/http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/index.php| archivedate =January 7, 2012}}</ref> of the sixteen four-year universities in the UNC system, WCU was founded to educate the people of the western North Carolina mountains.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina University| publisher =University of North Carolina| year =2008| url =http://online.northcarolina.edu/site.php?id=2981| access-date =2008-06-24| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20080620040831/http://online.northcarolina.edu/site.php?id=2981| archive-date =2008-06-20| url-status =dead}}</ref> WCU provides an education to students from 48 states and 35 countries.<ref>{{cite web| title =About WCU| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2013| url =http://www.wcu.edu/10.asp| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120419003909/http://www.wcu.edu/10.asp| archivedate =2012-04-19}}</ref> Enrollment for the Fall 2017 semester was 11,043 students.<ref>{{cite web | title=Western Carolina University enrollment tops 11,000 for new record| publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/2017/09/05/western-carolina-university-enrollment-tops-11-000-new-record/634260001/ |accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Joyner Building.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|[[Joyner Building|The Joyner Building]] served as a combination classroom, auditorium, and administration facility from its completion in 1913 until the 1930s, when other buildings relieved pressure from Joyner.  It was destroyed by fire in 1981, at which time it was the oldest building on campus.]]\n[[File:McKee School 1940.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|McKee Training School & Hoey Auditorium, two of many buildings on Campus built with help from the Works Progress Administration during the late 1930s and early 1940s.  McKee Hall, as it has since been rechristened, was named for [[Gertrude Dills McKee]], who was a great supporter of the University throughout her public life.]]\n\nIn 1888, the residents of Cullowhee desired a better school for the community than was offered in public schools of that day,<ref>{{Cite book| title =Western North Carolina: A History (1730\u20131913) | publisher =Overmountain Press| year =1966| url =https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog| page =[https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog/page/n459 438] }}</ref> organized a board of trustees\nand established a community school that came to be known as '''Cullowhee Academy'''.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite book| title =Western Carolina North Carolina: A History (1730\u20131913)| publisher =John Preston Arthur| year =1914| url =https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog| page =[https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog/page/n459 438]}}</ref> Founded in August 1889 as a semi-public secondary school and chartered as [[Smoky Mountain High School#Cullowhee High School|Cullowhee High School]] in 1891 (also called Cullowhee Academy), it served the Cullowhee community and boarding students from neighboring counties and other states.<ref>{{cite web| title =Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School | publisher =Hunter Library, Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/library/DigitalCollections/EducationWNC/cnis/}}</ref> The founder, Robert Lee Madison, wanted to provide an education for the young people in the region and train teachers to spread education throughout the western part of the state.<ref>{{cite web| title =Robert Lee Madison| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/1780.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= History of Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcuenglish.net/wcu_history/index.php?page=madison |date=August 23, 2012}}</ref> In 1893, through the efforts of Walter E. Moore,\nrepresentative from Jackson County, the North Carolina Legislature authorized an appropriation for the establishment of a normal department at the school \"for the purpose of training teachers\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> This designation became the first publicly funded [[normal school]] in North Carolina.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite web| title =Heritage & History | publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/227.asp}}</ref>\n\nIn 1905, the state assumed title to the school's buildings and property and made it a state institution. That same year, the school's name was changed to '''Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School'''. In 1925, the school's name was changed to '''Cullowhee State Normal School'''. During its years as Cullowhee Normal, the stated purpose of the school was to train teachers for the North Carolina public schools. A coeducational institution, Cullowhee Normal trained over two thousand teachers by the mid-1920s.<ref>{{cite web| title =Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School\n| publisher =Hunter Library| year =2008| url =http://library.wcu.edu/digitalcoll/education/cnis/Index.htm}}</ref>\n\nOver the next forty years, the school expanded its curriculum and evolved into a junior college, and in 1929 it was chartered by the Legislature as a four-year institution under the name '''Western Carolina Teachers College.''' Called \"the Cullowhee experiment\", Madison's idea became a model for the other regional colleges in the state.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/>\n\nThe demand for both liberal arts and other programs led to an expansion of the school's offerings.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\" /> Postgraduate studies and the Master of Arts in Education degree were added to the curriculum in 1951. In 1953, the name \"'''Western Carolina College'''\" was adopted.\n\nIn 1967, the institution was designated a regional university by the [[North Carolina General Assembly]] and given its current title, \"'''Western Carolina University'''.\"<ref>{{cite web| title =Strategic Planning/Mission Statement 2004 | publisher =Western Carolina University|date=January 2004| url =http://www.wcu.edu/chancellor/Strategic%20Planning-Mission%20Statement%202004.htm}}</ref> On July 1, 1972, WCU became a member of the [[University of North Carolina]] system.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina University| publisher =University of North Carolina| date =September 13, 2007| url =http://intranet.northcarolina.edu/docs/assessment/Profiles/2007-08/WCU_Inst._Profile_07-08_38.pdf| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081121003813/http://intranet.northcarolina.edu/docs/assessment/Profiles/2007-08/WCU_Inst._Profile_07-08_38.pdf| archivedate =November 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Precis of the university's history===\n{| cellpadding=4\n| '''Year''' || '''Name and Levels'''<ref>{{cite web| title =2006 Fact Book \u2013 Western Carolina University| publisher =University of North Carolina| date =November 10, 2006\n| url =http://www.wcu.edu/WebFiles/PDFs/OIPE_fboverview06.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1889 || Semi-private school\n|-\n| 1891 || Cullowhee High School\n|-\n| 1893 || First state appropriation; Normal Department established; First graduating class\n|-\n| 1905 || Cullowhee Normal and Industrial School\n|-\n| 1912 || Junior College rank established; Secondary school discontinued\n|-\n| 1913 || First college-level (one-year) degree awarded\n|-\n| 1925 || Cullowhee State Normal School\n|-\n| 1929 || Western Carolina Teachers College; Senior College rank established\n|-\n| 1931 || First Baccalaureate degree awarded\n|-\n| 1951 || Graduate degree established\n|-\n| 1952 || First master's degree awarded\n|-\n| 1953 || Western Carolina College\n|-\n| 1967 || Western Carolina University\n|-\n| 1972 || A constituent institution of the University of North Carolina\n|}\n\n==Facilities==\n===General location===\n[[File:Map of North Carolina highlighting Jackson County.svg|left|thumb|250px|Map of North Carolina highlighting Jackson County, NC]]\n\nWestern Carolina University is located in [[Jackson County, North Carolina|Jackson County]], in the [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] village of [[Cullowhee, North Carolina]]. The university operates learning centers in both [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] and [[Cherokee, North Carolina|Cherokee]] with programs offered online and at various [[community colleges]].<ref>{{cite web| title =Programs in Biltmore Park| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6249.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =Cherokee Center| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6306.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =Community College and Community Center | publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/2814.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =WCU, N.C. community colleges unveil comprehensive transfer | publisher =Western Carolina University| date =May 9, 2007 | url =http://www.wcu.edu/3242.asp}}</ref> The main campus is located in a valley of the [[Tuckasegee River]], between the [[Blue Ridge Mountains|Blue Ridge]] and [[Great Smoky Mountains]], {{convert|52|mi|km}} west of [[Asheville, North Carolina]] and 5 miles south of [[Sylva, NC]]. The university lies close to the [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]], the [[Blue Ridge Parkway]], the Eastern Band of Cherokee Indians Reservation (officially known as the [[Qualla Boundary]]), and some of the nation's most beautiful [[United States National Forest|national forest]] lands. At an elevation of {{convert|2100|ft|m}}, but located in a thermal valley, the campus enjoys the best of all four seasons but is shielded from most extreme temperatures by surrounding peaks. Cullowhee typically enjoys a rather mild winter season. In fact, Cullowhee can go some winters with little to no snowfall.<ref>{{cite web| title =1971\u20132000 Climate Normals CULLOWHEE, NORTH CAROLINA (312200)| publisher =State Climate Office of North Carolina| year =2012| url =http://www.nc-climate.ncsu.edu/cronos/normals.php?station=312200| access-date =2012-08-23| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130504064056/http://www.nc-climate.ncsu.edu/cronos/normals.php?station=312200| archive-date =2013-05-04| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile winters in the valley are generally mild, snow is not unusual in the higher elevations of Jackson County around [[Cashiers]] or [[Balsam, North Carolina|Balsam]]. In nearby Sapphire Valley, snowmaking machines maintain prime snow skiing conditions from mid-December through February. Locations in Jackson County are also within reasonable driving distance to ski slopes at [[Maggie Valley]]. The Blue Ridge Parkway is usually closed during winter weather, and has become popular with cross-country skiers during those times.<ref>{{cite web| title =A Photographic Journal of the Blue Ridge Parkway| publisher =Blue Ridge Parkway Guide| year =2008| url =http://www.virtualblueridge.com/photojournal/2004/01/31-001.asp}}</ref>\n\nThe many rivers, streams and forests surrounding Cullowhee, combined with the mild climate of Southern Appalachia, offer many opportunities for outdoor activities. Climbing, hiking, biking, rafting, kayaking, and camping are a few of the outdoor activities nearby.<ref>{{cite web| title =Outdoor Activities | publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/28442.asp}}</ref> Cities within a three-hour drive of campus include Atlanta, Georgia;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Atlanta&1s=GA&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Atlanta, GA to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> Charlotte, North Carolina;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Charlotte&1s=NC&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Charlotte, NC to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> Knoxville, Tennessee;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Knoxville&1s=TN&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Knoxville, TN to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> and Greenville, South Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Greenville&1s=SC&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Greenville, SC to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref>\n\n===Main campus in Cullowhee===\n[[File:WCU 2007.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|WCU 2007|Western Carolina University in 2007]]\n\nThe main campus in Cullowhee offers most of the amenities of a small town, including fourteen residence halls,<ref name=ResHalls>{{cite web | title =Residence Halls | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/8141.asp | year =2012}}</ref> two full-service cafeterias, a food court with fast-food outlets, health services, counseling, a bookstore, [[Hunter Library|library]], an swimming pool, tennis courts, movie theater, jogging trail and quarter-mile track, hiking and biking trails and intramural fields.\n\nThe campus center is the A.K. Hinds University Center.<ref>{{cite web | title =A.K. Hinds University Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/171.asp | year =2012}}</ref>  The UC contains the university post office, a movie theater, video and commuter lounges, student organization HQs including the Student Government Association and Last Minute Productions, meeting rooms and office spaces.  Outside of the UC is the \"Alumni Tower\", built in 1989, on the 100th birthday of the university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcu.edu/448.asp |title=Western Carolina University \u2013 Alumni Tower |publisher=Wcu.edu |date=October 28, 1989 |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> Other newly constructed facilities include the Center for Applied Technology (which houses new engineering laboratories); an expanded student life center; new athletic facilities; and a new student support center.\n\nA $13.5 million {{convert|73000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Student Recreation Center, was completed over the summer of 2008.<ref>{{cite web| title =Campus Recreation Center| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/7719.asp}}</ref> Harrill Residence Hall was renovated to add 6,000 square feet (557 m2) and bring the 1971 building to [[LEED standards]] of environmental friendliness and energy efficiency, and re-opened in fall 2012.\n\nThe new $46.2 million Health and Human Sciences Building opened for use at the start of the 2012\u201313 academic year, also built to LEED standards. This facility is the first project on the Millennial Initiative property and houses WCU's educational and outreach programs in the College of Health and Human Sciences. The four-story facility is home to the undergraduate and graduate programs in social work and communication sciences and disorders; graduate programs in physical therapy and health sciences; and undergraduate programs in athletic training, emergency medical care, environmental health, nutrition and dietetics, nursing and recreational therapy.<ref>{{cite web | title =Residence hall, new health building open for fall | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://news-prod.wcu.edu/2012/08/new-building-renovated-residence-hall-open/ | year=2012}}</ref>\n\n===Asheville campus===\nWCU's educational facilities in Asheville focus on professional and graduate degrees for working students.\n\n===Cherokee campus===\nThe Western Carolina University Cherokee Center in [[Cherokee, North Carolina]], was established in 1975 in cooperation with the tribal government of the Eastern Band of the Cherokee Indians.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina University Center in Cherokee| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6306.asp}}</ref> The center serves Cherokee and the surrounding communities and is available to all of the people of the region. Their services include the application process, transcript request, scholarships, internships placement, high school recruitment.\n\n==Organization and administration==\n[[File:Robert lee madison.jpg|left|150px|thumb|Robert Lee Madison, founder and first president]]\nThe university is led by Chancellor Kelli R. Brown, the chief administrative officer, along with Interim Provost and Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs Richard Starnes and several advisory groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wcu.edu/335.asp |title=Western Carolina University \u2013 Office of the Chancellor |publisher=Wcu.edu |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wcu.edu/334.asp |title=Western Carolina University \u2013 Office of the Provost |publisher=Wcu.edu |accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref> The institution operates under the guidance and policies of the Board of Trustees of Western Carolina University.<ref>{{cite web | title =Board of Trustees | url =http://www.wcu.edu/23798.asp | year =2012}}</ref> WCU also falls under the administration of University of North Carolina system president [[Thomas W. Ross]].  The university moved to a provost and senior vice chancellor model in 2004.\n\n===University media===\nThe university produces the following publications and broadcasts:\n* ''Western Carolina Magazine]:''<ref>{{cite web | title =Western Carolina Magazine | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://magazine.wcu.edu  | year =2012}}</ref> A seasonal publication primarily for alumni and friends of WCU, Western Carolina Magazine contains features on university people and programs, alumni updates, and news and events.\n* ''Inside WCU'':<ref>{{cite web | title =The Reporter | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://thereporter.wcu.edu | year =2012}}</ref> A weekly electronic newsletter for the faculty and staff of WCU, The Reporter features news, events and campus community updates.\n* ''MountainRise:''<ref>{{cite web | title =MountainRise | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/facctr/mountainrise/ | year =2012}}</ref> An open, peer-reviewed, international electronic journal published twice a year by the Coulter Faculty Center for Excellence in Teaching & Learning at Western Carolina University for the purpose of being an international vehicle for the Scholarship of Teaching & Learning (SoTL).\n* ''All-Western Carolina:'' The ''All-Western Carolina'' radio program airs during half-time of Catamount Sports Network broadcasts and highlights WCU's academic all-stars and happenings on campus.\n\nWCU students, faculty and staff also contribute to:\n*''WCU on iTunes U''<ref>{{cite web | title =WCU on iTunes U | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://itunes.wcu.edu/ | year =2009 | access-date =2012-08-24 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120924094603/http://itunes.wcu.edu/ | archive-date =2012-09-24 | url-status =dead }}</ref> Faculty and students are podcasting using WCU on iTunes U service from [[Apple Inc]]. This media repository was publicly listed on the [[iTunes U]] Colleges and Universities listings in August 2009.\n\n==Academics and research==\n\n===Academic structure===\nWestern Carolina University\u2019s academic programs are housed in six colleges: Arts and Sciences, Business, Education and Allied Professions, Fine and Performing Arts, Health and Human Sciences, and Engineering and Technology. WCU also has an Honors College and Graduate School, and offers several interdisciplinary programs:<ref>{{cite web | title =Western Carolina University \u2013 Departments, Schools and Colleges | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/42.asp}}</ref>\n\n*College of Health and Human Sciences\n**Communication Sciences and Disorders\n**School of Health Sciences\n***Emergency Medical Care\n**School of Nursing\n**Physical Therapy\n**Social Work\n*College of Arts and Sciences\n**Anthropology and Sociology\n**Biology\n**Chemistry and Physics\n**Communication\n**Criminology and Criminal Justice\n**English\n**Geosciences and Natural Resources\n**History\n**Mathematics and Computer Science\n**World Languages\n**Philosophy and Religion\n**Political Science and Public Affairs\n*College of Fine and Performing Arts\n**Department of Stage and Screen\n**School of Art and Design\n**School of Music\n*College of Business\n**Accounting, Finance, Information Systems and Economics\n**Business Administration and Law and Sport Management\n**Entrepreneurship, Sales and Marketing, and Hospitality and Tourism\n***Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation\n***Center for Professional Selling and Marketing\n**Global Management and Strategy\n**Sales and Marketing\n***Center for Professional Selling and Marketing\n*College of Education and Allied Professions\n**School of Teaching and Learning\n**Human Services\n**Psychology\n*College of Engineering and Technology\n*The Kimmel School of Construction Management\n*The Honors College\n*The Graduate School\n*Interdisciplinary Programs: Science Education, Social Sciences Education, Environmental Sciences, Forensic Science, and International Studies, Integrated Health Sciences\n\n===Academic programs===\nWith its main campus located on the site of an ancient Cherokee Indian village<ref>{{cite web| title =Students Sift Through Centuries at Mound Site on Western Carolina's Campus| publisher =Western Carolina University| date =July 2, 2003| url =http://www.wcu.edu/pubinfo/news/mounddig.htm}}</ref> and adjacent to the Great Smoky and Blue Ridge Mountains, Western Carolina has a commitment to the rich traditions of both the [[Appalachia]]n and [[Cherokee]] cultures. The university's Mountain Heritage Center;<ref name=\"Mountain Heritage Center\">{{cite web | title =Mountain Heritage Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/2389.asp | year =2012}}</ref> Cherokee Center;<ref>{{cite web | title =Cherokee Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6306.asp | year =2012}}</ref> Craft Revival Project;<ref>{{cite web | title =Craft Revival Project | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/library/DigitalCollections/CraftRevival/index.htm | year =2012}}</ref> Cherokee Studies Program<ref>{{cite web | title =Cherokee Studies Program | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6302.asp | year =2012}}</ref> and WCU's partnership to preserve the Cherokee language<ref>{{cite web| title =Preserving the Cherokee Language| publisher =Western Carolina University| url =http://www.wcu.edu/298.asp | year =2012}}</ref> all reflect that influence \u2013 and provide educational resources for the region.<ref>{{cite web| title =University Awards and Accolades| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2009| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6620.asp}}</ref>\n\nWestern is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"M1: Master's Colleges and Universities \u2013 Larger programs\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Western Carolina University |publisher=[[Indiana University]] |date=2020 |url=https://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=200004}}</ref> and in the elective \"community engagement\" category.<ref>{{cite web| title =Carnegie Foundation recognizes WCU for community engagement | publisher =Western Carolina University| date =December 19, 2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/12218.asp}}</ref> WCU is accredited by the Commission on Colleges of the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]] to award degrees at the bachelor, masters, intermediate, and doctoral levels. The university holds 21 program accreditations and is a member of more than 30 state and national associations and organizations to which its professional programs are related. In 2009, the Corporation for National and Community Service recognized WCU by awarding the President's Higher Education Community Service Honor Roll with Distinction for \"exemplary commitment to service and civic engagement\" on WCU's campus and beyond.<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU recognized with distinction on national honor roll for service| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2009| url =http://www.wcu.edu/12941.asp}}</ref>\n\nAs the sixth-largest producer of teachers in North Carolina, the College of Education and Allied Professions was the national winner of the Association of Teacher Educators' Distinguished Program in Teacher Education Award<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU Teacher Education Program is Recipient of National Award | publisher =Western Carolina University| date =February 24, 2006\n| url =http://www.wcu.edu/pubinfo/news/2006/CEAPnationalaward.htm}}</ref> in 2006.  The college is also the 2007 co-winner of the Christa McAuliffe Excellence in Teacher Education Award<ref>{{cite web| title =Teacher education program wins national Christa McAuliffe Award| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/5183.asp}}</ref> presented by the American Association of State Colleges and Universities. The Christa McAuliffe Award nationally recognizes outstanding programs in teacher education at AASCU member institutions.\n\nWestern Carolina's Forensic Research Facility (commonly referred to as the \"FoREST\") is just the second facility of its kind nationally.<ref>{{cite web| title =Forensic Research Facility| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/293.asp}}</ref> The decomposition research station is an extremely valuable resource for researchers and forensic anthropology students to study natural decomposition.\n\nThe residential Honors College was first of its kind in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web| title =Only at WCU| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/28.asp}}</ref> Newly accepted students are invited to live in one of two exclusive residence halls on campus. The Honors College is one of a few in the state to offer a residential option and among a few nationwide to award graduates with a special honors diploma. The college began in 1998 with 77 students and has grown to approximately 1,400. For entering freshman, the Honor's College average weighted GPA is over 4.00 and the average SAT score is 1380.  The College is a member of the National Collegiate Honors Council.<ref>{{cite web | title =Member Institutions \u2013 National Collegiate Honors Council | publisher =National Collegiate Honors Council | url =http://nchchonors.org/members-area/member-institutions-4/ | year =2012 | access-date =2012-08-23 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120902224619/http://nchchonors.org/members-area/member-institutions-4/ | archive-date =2012-09-02 | url-status =dead }}</ref>  In August 2009, Balsam Hall, the first part of a $50.2 million Honors College residential community located at the center of campus opened, housing 426 students. In Fall 2010, Blue Ridge Hall completed the community and add an additional 400 beds for Honors College students and Teaching Fellows.<ref>{{cite web| title =Balsam Hall opens to first 298 residents| publisher =the Reporter| year =2009| url =http://thereporter.wcu.edu/2009/08/new-residence-hall-opens-to-first-298-students/}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2000, WCU was officially designated a [[National Merit]] sponsoring university, just the fourth institution of higher education in North Carolina, public or private, to receive that distinction<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU Becomes 4TH National Merit Sponsor Among N.C. Universities| publisher =Western Carolina University| date =April 12, 2000| url =http://www.wcu.edu/pubinfo/news/merit.html}}</ref>  The university grants scholarships to students who qualify as National Merit Finalists. The Western Meritorious Award for Finalists provides a four-year scholarship, which covers the equivalent amount of in-state tuition, fees, room, and board, to National Merit Finalists, who also receive a computer.\n\nThe 2012 edition of the U.S. News & World Report guide to \"America's Best Colleges\" ranks Western Carolina University 14th<ref>{{cite web| title =U.S. News and World Report Best Colleges 2012| publisher =U.S. News and World Report| date =August 2012| url =http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/rankings/regional-universities-south/top-public}}</ref>  among public universities in the South that offer master's degrees.\n\nIn 2015, the [[North Carolina General Assembly]] approved the the NC Promise Tuition Plan, a tuition reduction plan to make three universities  - WCU, [[Elizabeth City State University]], and [[University of North Carolina at Pembroke]] - more affordable and accessible. The NC Promise began in the fall semester of 2018 and drastically reduces the tuition cost for students. In-state students pay $500 a semester and out-of-state students pay $2,500 a semester.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcarolina.edu/Prospective-Students/NC-Promise|title=NC Promise {{!}} UNC System Office|website=www.northcarolina.edu|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> Attendance has increased for three consecutive years with the total attendance as of Fall 2019 at 12,167 students (10,469 undergraduate and 1,698 graduate students).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcu.edu/discover/about/fast-facts.aspx|title=Western Carolina University|website=Fast Facts|language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\n===Centers, institutes, and affiliates===\nCommunity focus, scholarly research, business development, preservation of the Cherokee & Appalachian Mountain cultures, and the advancement of technology & public policy are the guiding foci of Western Carolina's Centers, Institutes & Affiliates.<ref>{{cite web | title =Centers, Institutes and Affiliates | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/223.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n\n*Center for Rapid Product Realization<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for Rapid Product Realization | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/3632.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n**Carolinas MicroOptics Triangle\n**Carolinas Photonics Consortium\n*Center for Study of Free Enterprise \n*Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/3857.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center of Professional Selling and Marketing<ref>{{cite web | title =Center of Professional Selling and Marketing | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/12975.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center for Math/Science Education<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for Math/Science Education | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6087.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Cherokee Studies<ref>{{cite web | title =Cherokee Studies | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6302.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n**Projects and Initiatives from Cherokee Studies\n**Cherokee Studies Academic Programs\n**Cherokee Center\n**Revitalization of Traditional Cherokee Artisan Resources\n*John W. Bardo Fine & Performing Arts Center<ref>{{cite web | title =John W. Bardo Fine and Performing Arts Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/bardoartscenter/index.html | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center for the Support of Beginning Teachers<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for the Support of Beginning Teachers | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/7585.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Mountain Heritage Center<ref name=\"Mountain Heritage Center\"/>\n*The Public Policy Institute<ref>{{cite web | title =The Public Policy Institute | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/9355.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Ramsey Regional Activities Center<ref>{{cite web | title=Ramsey Regional Activities Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url=http://ramsey.wcu.edu/ | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Small Business & Technology Development Center<ref>{{cite web | title =Small Business & Technology Development Center | publisher =University of North Carolina system | url =http://www.sbtdc.org/ | year =2012}}</ref> partner\n*Writing and Learning Commons<ref>{{cite web | title=Writing and Learning Commons | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/29229.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Program for the Study of Developed Shorelines<ref>{{cite web | title =Program for the Study of Developed Shorelines | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/1037.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Speech and Hearing Clinic<ref>{{cite web | title =Speech and Hearing Clinic | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/8393.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Myron L. Coulter Faculty Commons for Excellence in Teaching and Learning<ref>{{cite web | title =Coulter Faculty Commons | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/7072.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Southern Appalachian Biodiversity and Ecology Center<ref>{{cite web | title =Southern Appalachian Biodiversity and Ecology Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url=http://www.wcu.edu/7401.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center for Service Learning and Community Engagement<ref>{{cite web | title=Center for Service Learning | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/9815.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Local Government Training Program<ref>{{cite web | title =Local Government Training Program | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/10147.asp |year =2012}}</ref>\n*Mountain Area Pro Bono Health Care\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Residential life===\nThe main campus at Cullowhee has residential facilities for students. These include thirteen residence halls,<ref name=ResHalls /> two full-service cafeterias, and one food court with fast-food outlets. The halls house more than 4,500 WCU students each academic year.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wcu.edu/discover/about/fast-facts.aspx | title = Fast Facts | work = About Western Carolina University | publisher = Western Carolina University | date = | access-date = May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe campus residence buildings include one for graduate students and one for married students. Special residence accommodations include honors residence halls and The Village, home to residential Greek and student organizations. Three new residence facilities were recently completed from a $50.2 million residence hall project. The two newest residence halls on campus are Balsam Residence Hall and Blue Ridge Residence Hall.<ref>{{cite web| title =Ground-breaking ceremony held for $50.2 million residence hall project| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/7184.asp}}</ref> The $18 million {{convert|53000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} campus dining facility was opened in stages beginning in July 2009.<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU Prepares for 1,600 students at Freshman Move-in Day| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2009| url =http://www.wcu.edu/24854.asp}}</ref>\n\n===Athletics===\n{{Main|Western Carolina Catamounts}}\n[[File:Ramsey Regional Activity Center in Cullowhee, NC.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Ramsey Center basketball and volleyball arena]]\n\nAs a member of the [[Southern Conference]], Western Carolina University participates in [[National Collegiate Athletics Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] athletics.  Intercollegiate athletics include football, men and women's basketball, baseball, softball, women's soccer, men and women's golf, men and women's track and field (Indoor and Outdoor), cross country running, women's volleyball and tennis. Catamount football is a member of [[Division I FCS]] and plays at Whitmire Stadium. The Ramsey Center is home to men's and women's basketball, and women's volleyball. Baseball is played at Hennon Stadium, softball is played at the Catamount Softball Complex, and the Catamount Athletic Complex is home to women's soccer, tennis, and track and field.\n\nOn November 29, 1980, Western Carolina's Ronnie Carr made the first intercollegiate three-point field goal, in a game against [[Middle Tennessee State University]], a game WCU won 77\u201370.<ref>{{cite web| title =Three-point era got its start with Ronnie Carr| publisher =Rivals.com| date =May 21, 2007| url =http://collegebasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=675171| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120309172943/http://collegebasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=675171| archivedate =March 9, 2012}}</ref> The ball he used is on display at the [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] in Springfield, Massachusetts.\n\nWestern Carolina and [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] have a football rivalry in which they once competed in the [[Battle for the Old Mountain Jug]] on an annual basis.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina Announces 2008 Schedule| publisher =College Sporting News| year =2008| url =http://www.collegesportingnews.com/article.asp?articleid=89747}}</ref> The Catamounts football team was runner-up in the [[Division I-AA]] National Football Championship Game in 1983.<ref>{{cite web | title =1983\u201384 FCS Championship | url =http://www.fanbase.com/128297-1983-12-17 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20130122204602/http://www.fanbase.com/128297-1983-12-17 | url-status =dead | archive-date =2013-01-22 | year =2011 }}</ref>\n\nCurrent NCAA sports at WCU include:\n* Men - Baseball, Basketball, Cross Country, Football, Golf, Track and Field\n* Women - Basketball, Cross Country, Golf, Soccer, Softball, Tennis, Track and Field, Volleyball\n\nIn addition to NCAA athletics, Western Carolina University is also home to many different club sports, intramurals, and a dance team, including the following:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Aquatics (Swimming)\n* Ballroom Dance\n* Dance (Jazz)<ref name=\"dance\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZJ9ETLRBYcY https://www.youtube.com] 2015-2016 Western Carolina University Dance Team: Road to Nationals.</ref>\n* Disc Golf\n* Equestrian\n* Fencing\n* Kendo\n* Men's Soccer\n* Men's Rugby\n* Men's Lacrosse\n* Mountain Biking\n* Ultimate Frisbee\n* Women's Lacrosse\n* Women's Rugby\n* Women's Volleyball\n* Wrestling\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn 2016 the WCU dance team won third place at the [[National Dance Alliance|NDA Nationals dance competition]], performing in [[Daytona Beach, Florida]].<ref name=\"dance\"/><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TyAFizag9ls https://www.youtube.com] WCU Dance Team - NDA 2016 - Daytona Beach.</ref>\n\n===Music===\n\n====Concerts and recitals====\nThe Schools of Music and Fine and Performing Arts offer a variety of events featuring students, faculty, and outside performers. These cultural opportunities are typically relatively cheap, and students can often attend them free of charge.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150227170530/http://www.wcu.edu/academics/departments-schools-colleges/FPA/schools-departments-and-centers/music/prospective-music-students/music-ensembles/]</ref>\n\n====Pride of the Mountains====\n{{Main|Western Carolina University Pride of the Mountains Marching Band}}\n\nThe Pride of the Mountains is the largest college marching band in the Carolinas and Tennessee. As of Fall 2014, the marching band includes just over 500 members, making it one of the largest marching bands in the United States.  The band is open to all Western Carolina students regardless of class or major, with approximately 60% of its members non-music majors.\n\nIn 2014, the band performed in the [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] with 510 band members participating. Announcers described their performance as \"This is the largest band this parade has seen in decades\", \"This is the best of the best\", and \"They don't mess around at Western Carolina\".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fuszup1CQfc https://www.youtube.com] Western Carolina University at Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade (2014).</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F_slJVRp41g https://www.youtube.com] Pride of the Mountains Marching Band at Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Pride of the Mountains to participate in Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade | publisher =Western Carolina University | url = http://news-prod.wcu.edu/2013/04/pride-of-the-mountains-to-participate-in-2014-macys-thanksgiving-parade/ | year=2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Pride of the Mountains also performed at a [[Carolina Panthers]] halftime show in 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=SLIDESHOW: Band marches at NFL game | publisher =Western Carolina University The Reporter | url = http://thereporter.wcu.edu/2011/09/slideshow-band-marches-at-nfl-game/ | year=2011}}</ref> The band was also the special guest at the [[Bands of America]] Grand National Championships in Indianapolis in 1998, 2003, 2008 and 2012, an honor given to only one college band in the United States each year. In addition, the band was also a special guest at the [[Bands of America]] Regional's held in Atlanta in 1995, 2006, 2010, and 2011.  In 2009, the Pride of the Mountains was selected as one of the five best collegiate marching bands in the nation by the College Band Directors National Association and featured in the book \"Marching Bands and Drumlines: Secrets of Success from the Best of the Best\" by Paul Buyer.\n\nThe band is the 2009 recipient of the [[Sudler Trophy]] awarded by the [[John Philip Sousa Foundation]].<ref name=\"CTHeisman\">{{cite web| title =WCU band wins 'Heisman' of marching bands| publisher =The Asheville Citizen-Time| year =2009| url =http://www.citizen-times.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090528/MOUNTAINNEWS/905280318}}</ref> They participated in the 2011 Tournament of Roses Parade in Pasadena, California, and won the most votes in a \"best band\" in the parade poll hosted by KTLA-TV.<ref>{{cite web | title =The Pride wins favorite band poll, returns home | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://roseparade.wcu.edu/the-pride-wins-favorite-band-poll-returns-home/ | year =2011}}</ref>\n\n===Greek life===\nWCU is home to a wide range of Greek [[fraternities]] and [[sororities]], as well as several councils and societies.<ref>{{cite web | title =Greek Life at WCU | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/12520.asp | year =2012}}</ref> The Greek community offers many social opportunities to enrich college life. Greeks get personal guidance in planning their curriculum and choosing classes and instructors, and assistance with registration and financial aid. Chapter study sessions, educational programs, tutoring, and study partners and teams offer support for developing and maintaining [[study skills]]. Greeks are recognized for their academic successes through Greek scholarship and awards programs and honor societies such as the Order of Omega. According to 2011\u201312 figures from ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'', 3.4% of WCU's male undergraduate students are in fraternities, while 3.6% of female undergraduate students are in sororities.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web| title =America's Best Colleges 2008: Western Carolina University: At a glance| publisher =usnews.com | year =2012| url =http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/western-carolina-university-2981}}</ref>\n\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''Sororities'''\n*College Panhellenic Council (CPC)\n**[[Alpha Chi Omega]]\n**[[Alpha Gamma Delta]]\n**[[Alpha Xi Delta]]\n**[[Delta Zeta]]\n**[[Phi Mu]]\n**[[Kappa Delta]] (inactive)\n**[[Sigma Kappa]] (inactive)\n**[[Zeta Tau Alpha]] (inactive)\n\n'''Greek Councils & Societies'''\n*IFC\n*CPC\n*NPHC\n*[[Order of Omega]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''Fraternities'''\n*[[North American Interfraternity Conference]] (IFC)\n**[[Delta Sigma Phi]]\n**[[Kappa Alpha Order]]\n**[[Lambda Chi Alpha]]\n**[[Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia]] \n**[[Pi Kappa Phi]]\n**[[Pi Lambda Phi]]\n**[[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]]\n**[[Sigma Chi]]\n**[[Theta Xi]]\n**[[Alpha Sigma Phi]] (colony)\n**[[Delta Chi]] (inactive)\n**[[Kappa Sigma]] (inactive)\n**[[Pi Kappa Alpha]] (inactive)\n**[[Sigma Nu]] (inactive)\n**[[Sigma Phi Epsilon]] (inactive)\n**[[Tau Kappa Epsilon]] (inactive)\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''Historically Black Fraternities'''\n*[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC)\n**[[Alpha Phi Alpha]]\n**[[Omega Psi Phi]]\n**[[Phi Beta Sigma]]\n**[[Kappa Alpha Psi]]\n**[[Phi Beta Sigma]] (inactive)\n'''Historically Black Sororities'''\n*[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC)\n**[[Alpha Kappa Alpha]]\n**[[Zeta Phi Beta]]\n**[[Delta Sigma Theta]] (inactive)\n\n'''[[Professional Fraternity Association]]'''\n*[[Phi Sigma Pi]] National Co-Ed Honors Fraternity<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://professionalfraternity.org/fraternal-members |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123115441/http://professionalfraternity.org/fraternal-members |archive-date=2016-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n'''No Council Affiliation'''\n*[[Sigma Alpha Omega]] (fraternity)\n*[[Epsilon Tau Pi]] (fraternity)\n*[[Alpha Pi Omega]] (sorority)\n|}\n\n===WCU student media===\nHoused in the Student Media Center (Old Student Union) on the hill area of campus are WCU's Student Media Organizations, which are open to all students and are produced by students.<ref>{{cite web | title =Student Media | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/108.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\nThe following organizations are a part of WCU Student Media:\n*'''WWCU-FM:''' [[WWCU]]-FM, Power 90.5, is the broadcast service of WCU and broadcasts 24 hours a day, 7 days a week as Jackson County's only FM radio station.\n* '''WCAT:''' Cable & Internet radio station offering an eclectic mix of music chosen by student DJs, as well as original talk shows and artist interviews. It broadcasts on the campus closed-circuit television station 22.\n* '''TV 62:''' The student-run campus television station, offering original programing to the campus on channel 62. It is WCU's closed-circuit television station with offices located in the A.K. Hinds University Center, an organization offering original programming that allows students to showcase their short films, as well as announce events on campus and highlight recent sporting events.\n* '''''The Nomad:''''' WCU's Literature & Art magazine, published once a year in the Spring semester. Student staff members work together to produce and distribute WCU's student literary magazine.\n* '''''The Gadfly:''''' WCU's Journal of Social Criticism and Philosophy. Satirical pieces philosophically critiquing society-at-large in a humorous manner. Published once a semester.<ref>{{cite web | title =The Gadfly | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/11994.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n* '''''Western Carolinian Newspaper:''''' A bi-weekly newspaper focusing on news and events relevant to the campus and surrounding community. Includes News, Features, Sports, and Arts & Entertainment sections. Available in print in the local area and on-line at www.westerncarolinian.com.<ref>{{cite web | title =Western Carolinian | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.westerncarolinian.com/ | year =2012}}</ref>\n* '''''The Western Carolina Journalist:''''' An online newspaper ran by the Communication department covering news about WCU and the surrounding areas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewesterncarolinajournalist.com/ |title=The Western Carolina Journalist |publisher=Thewesterncarolinajournalist.com |date=2014-05-31 |accessdate=2014-08-24}}</ref>\n*'''''The Tuckasegee Valley Historical Review''''': The Tuckasegee Valley Historical Review is an annually published graduate history journal. The review publishes articles by WCU graduate students in history with a primarily local focus.<ref>{{cite web | title =Tuckasegee Valley Historical Review | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/8152.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n===Alumni===\n\n*[[Gerald Austin]] \u2013 [[National Football League|NFL]] referee\n*[[Bobbi Baker]] \u2013 actress, best known for her role as Kiki on the Tyler Perry sitcom ''[[House of Payne]]''\n*[[James A. Beaty, Jr.]] \u2013 current U.S. District Judge and former nominee to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]\n*[[Dean Biasucci]] \u2013 athlete (former placekicker, NFL [[Indianapolis Colts]]), actor\n*[[Linda L. Bray]] \u2013 first female in the military to lead troops into combat\n*[[Sean Bridgers]] \u2013 actor, writer, director, producer\n*[[Andrew C. Brock]] \u2013 [[North Carolina Senate|North Carolina State Senator]]\n*[[Jared Burton]] \u2013 retired [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] [[pitcher]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/burtoja01.shtml|title= Jared Burton|publisher= Baseball-Reference.Com|accessdate= October 3, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Keion Crossen]] - cornerback, [[Houston Texans]]\n*[[Geoff Collins (American football)|Geoff Collins]] - head football coach at [[Georgia Tech]]\n*[[Ariana DeBose]] \u2013 actress, singer, and dancer\n*[[Louis Ducruet]]- scout at [[AS Monaco FC]], 12th in line to the Monagesque throne, grandson to Rainier III, Prince of Monaco and American actress Grace Kelly\n*[[Carol Fowler Durham]] \u2013 professor of Nursing at [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], interprofessional teams expert\n*[[Joe Firstman]] \u2013 musician and musical director\n*[[Ernest A. Fitzgerald]] (1947) \u2013 bishop of the [[United Methodist Church]]\n*[[Judy Green (volleyball coach)|Judy Green]] \u2013 head volleyball coach for the [[University of Alabama]]\n*[[Mel Gibson (basketball)|Mel Gibson]] \u2013 former basketball player for the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n*[[Rich Hall]] \u2013 comedian, writer\n*[[Greg Holland (baseball)|Greg Holland]] \u2013 MLB pitcher and MLB All-Star\n*[[Brad Hoover]] \u2013 former fullback for the NFL [[Carolina Panthers]]\n*[[Frank Huguelet]] \u2013 retired professional wrestler (as \"'Heavy Metal' Ric Savage'\"), television host\n*[[Sarah Hutchings]] \u2013 Composer\n*[[Paul Johnson (American football coach)|Paul Johnson]] \u2013 head football coach at [[Georgia Tech]]\n*[[Jeanne Jolly]] \u2013 singer, songwriter\n*[[Tony Jones (football player)|Tony Jones]] \u2013 football player with the NFL [[Denver Broncos]]\n*[[Andrew Jordan (football player)|Andrew Jordan]] \u2013 [[tight end]] in the NFL\n*[[David Joy (author)|David Joy]] \u2013 author\n*[[Keith LeClair]] \u2013 athlete and baseball coach at Western Carolina University\n*[[Henry Logan (basketball)|Henry Logan]] \u2013 athlete; in 1964 became North Carolina's first African-American collegiate athlete, and the first to play basketball for a \"white\" public institution in 1964\n*[[Kevin Martin (basketball, born 1983)|Kevin Martin]] \u2013 professional basketball player<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/martike02.html|title = Kevin Martin|publisher= Basketball=Reference.com|accessdate= December 21, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Manteo Mitchell]] \u2013 track and field athlete, 2012 London Olympic medalist\n*[[Percy Watson|Nick McNeil]] \u2013 former NFL player, [[WWE]] professional wrestler (as '\"Showtime!' Percy Watson\")\n*[[Mary Cordell Nesbitt]] \u2013 politician\n*[[David Patten]] \u2013 NFL wide receiver\n*[[Dave Pember]] \u2013 former pitcher for MLB [[Milwaukee Brewers]]\n*[[J. T. Poston]] - [[professional golfer]]\n*[[Rachel Reilly (Big Brother)|Rachel Reilly]] \u2013 reality television show contestant, television host\n*[[David Sedaris]] \u2013 humorist, comedian, author, and radio contributor\n*[[Geno Segers]] \u2013 former professional rugby player, actor.\n*[[Clyde Simmons]] \u2013 defensive end for the NFL [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n*[[Tim Sinicki]] \u2013 head baseball coach at intercollegiate [[Binghamton Bearcats baseball|Binghamton]]<ref name=sinicki>{{cite news|last1=Mangan|first1=Mike|title=Five Questions: Binghamton University's Tim Sinicki|url=http://www.pressconnects.com/article/20140603/SPORTS03/306030015/Five-Questions-Binghamton-University-s-Tim-Sinicki|accessdate=June 28, 2014|work=PressConnects.com|publisher=Press & Sun-Bulletin|date=June 3, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QfYd0g5u?url=http://www.pressconnects.com/article/20140603/SPORTS03/306030015/Five-Questions-Binghamton-University-s-Tim-Sinicki?nclick_check=1|archivedate=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Matt Stillwell]] \u2013 Nashville recording artist\n*[[Wayne Tolleson]] \u2013 [[Major League Baseball]] player 1981-1990\n*[[Willie Williams (American football)|Willie Williams]] \u2013 NFL defensive back for [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n\n===Faculty===\n*[[Robert J. Conley]] \u2013 award-winning author\n*[[Terrance Mann]] \u2013 stage actor, director, singer, songwriter, and dancer\n*[[Ron Rash]] \u2013 award-winning author\n*[[Laura Wright (academic)|Laura Wright]] \u2013 founder of academic field of [[vegan studies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.wcu.edu}}\n*[http://www.catamountsports.com Western Carolina Athletics website]\n\n{{Western Carolina University}}\n{{University of North Carolina}}\n{{Southern Conference navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1889]]\n[[Category:Education in Jackson County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Western Carolina University]]\n[[Category:Education in Asheville, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Education in Swain County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Jackson County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1889 establishments in North Carolina]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Western Carolina University\n| image_name = Western Carolina University seal.png\n| image_size = 150px\n| established = 1889\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| parent = [[University of North Carolina|UNC System]]\n| endowment = $66 million<ref>As of June 30, 2016. {{cite web |url=http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016-Endowment-Market-Values.pdf |title=U.S. and Canadian Institutions Listed by Fiscal Year (FY) 2016 Endowment Market Value and Change in Endowment Market Value from FY 2015 to FY 2016 |publisher=National Association of College and University Business Officers and Commonfund Institute |year=2017 |access-date=2017-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215040947/http://www.nacubo.org/Documents/EndowmentFiles/2016%2DEndowment%2DMarket%2DValues.pdf |archive-date=2017-02-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| chancellor = Kelli R. Brown\n| provost = Richard Starnes (Interim)\n| faculty = 639<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web| title =2007 Fact Book and University Data| publisher =WCU| year =2008| url =http://planning.wcu.edu/2007_Factbook/Employees_Binder.pdf}}</ref>\n| staff = 967<ref name=\"autogenerated3\" />\n| city = [[Cullowhee, North Carolina|Cullowhee]]\n| state = [[North Carolina]]\n| country = United States\n| coor = {{Coord|35|18|35|N|83|11|00|W|region:US-NC_type:edu|display=inline,title}}\n| students = 12,167\n| undergrad = 10,469\n| postgrad = 1,698<ref name=\"Fast Facts\">{{cite web|title=Fast Facts|url=http://www.wcu.edu/discover/about/fast-facts.aspx|website=About Western Carolina|publisher=Western Carolina University|accessdate=7 December 2017}}</ref>\n| campus = Rural/[[Valley]]<br>{{convert|589|acre|km2}}\n| athletics = [[NCAA Division I]] [[Football Championship Subdivision|FCS]] \u2013 [[Southern Conference|SoCon]]\n| sports = 16 varsity teams\n| nickname = [[Western Carolina Catamounts|Catamounts]]\n| colors = Purple and Gold<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150103082905/http://www.wcu.edu/WebFiles/PDFs/Athleticsbrandstyleguidev4.pdf]</ref><br/>{{color box|#592C88}}&nbsp;{{color box|#C1A875}}\n| website = {{url|www.wcu.edu}}\n| logo = [[File:Western Carolina University Logo.svg|250px]]\n| former_names = Cullowhee Academy (1889\u20131905)<br>Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School (1905\u20131925)<br>Cullowhee State Normal School (1925\u20131929)<br>Western Carolina Teachers College (1929\u20131953)<br>Western Carolina College (1953\u20131967)\n}}\n\n'''Western Carolina University''' ('''WCU''') is a [[public university]] in [[Cullowhee, North Carolina]]. It is part of the [[University of North Carolina]] system.<ref>{{cite web| title =University of North Carolina| date =August 23, 2012| url =http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/INST_WCU.php| access-date =2012-08-23| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20121013145428/http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/INST_WCU.php| archive-date =2012-10-13| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth oldest institution<ref>{{cite web| title =Our 17 Institutions| publisher =The University of North Carolina| date =August 23, 2012| url =http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/index.php| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120107134507/http://www.northcarolina.edu/campus_profiles/index.php| archivedate =January 7, 2012}}</ref> of the sixteen four-year universities in the UNC system, WCU was founded to educate the people of the western North Carolina mountains.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina University| publisher =University of North Carolina| year =2008| url =http://online.northcarolina.edu/site.php?id=2981| access-date =2008-06-24| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20080620040831/http://online.northcarolina.edu/site.php?id=2981| archive-date =2008-06-20| url-status =dead}}</ref> WCU provides an education to students from 48 states and 35 countries.<ref>{{cite web| title =About WCU| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2013| url =http://www.wcu.edu/10.asp| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120419003909/http://www.wcu.edu/10.asp| archivedate =2012-04-19}}</ref> Enrollment for the Fall 2017 semester was 11,043 students.<ref>{{cite web | title=Western Carolina University enrollment tops 11,000 for new record| publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/2017/09/05/western-carolina-university-enrollment-tops-11-000-new-record/634260001/ |accessdate=September 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Joyner Building.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|[[Joyner Building|The Joyner Building]] served as a combination classroom, auditorium, and administration facility from its completion in 1913 until the 1930s, when other buildings relieved pressure from Joyner.  It was destroyed by fire in 1981, at which time it was the oldest building on campus.]]\n[[File:McKee School 1940.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|McKee Training School & Hoey Auditorium, two of many buildings on Campus built with help from the Works Progress Administration during the late 1930s and early 1940s.  McKee Hall, as it has since been rechristened, was named for [[Gertrude Dills McKee]], who was a great supporter of the University throughout her public life.]]\n\nIn 1888, the residents of Cullowhee desired a better school for the community than was offered in public schools of that day,<ref>{{Cite book| title =Western North Carolina: A History (1730\u20131913) | publisher =Overmountain Press| year =1966| url =https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog| page =[https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog/page/n459 438] }}</ref> organized a board of trustees\nand established a community school that came to be known as '''Cullowhee Academy'''.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite book| title =Western Carolina North Carolina: A History (1730\u20131913)| publisher =John Preston Arthur| year =1914| url =https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog| page =[https://archive.org/details/westernnorthcar00arthgoog/page/n459 438]}}</ref> Founded in August 1889 as a semi-public secondary school and chartered as [[Smoky Mountain High School#Cullowhee High School|Cullowhee High School]] in 1891 (also called Cullowhee Academy), it served the Cullowhee community and boarding students from neighboring counties and other states.<ref>{{cite web| title =Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School | publisher =Hunter Library, Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/library/DigitalCollections/EducationWNC/cnis/}}</ref> The founder, Robert Lee Madison, wanted to provide an education for the young people in the region and train teachers to spread education throughout the western part of the state.<ref>{{cite web| title =Robert Lee Madison| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/1780.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title= History of Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcuenglish.net/wcu_history/index.php?page=madison |date=August 23, 2012}}</ref> In 1893, through the efforts of Walter E. Moore,\nrepresentative from Jackson County, the North Carolina Legislature authorized an appropriation for the establishment of a normal department at the school \"for the purpose of training teachers\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> This designation became the first publicly funded [[normal school]] in North Carolina.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite web| title =Heritage & History | publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/227.asp}}</ref>\n\nIn 1905, the state assumed title to the school's buildings and property and made it a state institution. That same year, the school's name was changed to '''Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School'''. In 1925, the school's name was changed to '''Cullowhee State Normal School'''. During its years as Cullowhee Normal, the stated purpose of the school was to train teachers for the North Carolina public schools. A coeducational institution, Cullowhee Normal trained over two thousand teachers by the mid-1920s.<ref>{{cite web| title =Cullowhee Normal & Industrial School\n| publisher =Hunter Library| year =2008| url =http://library.wcu.edu/digitalcoll/education/cnis/Index.htm}}</ref>\n\nOver the next forty years, the school expanded its curriculum and evolved into a junior college, and in 1929 it was chartered by the Legislature as a four-year institution under the name '''Western Carolina Teachers College.''' Called \"the Cullowhee experiment\", Madison's idea became a model for the other regional colleges in the state.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\"/>\n\nThe demand for both liberal arts and other programs led to an expansion of the school's offerings.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\" /> Postgraduate studies and the Master of Arts in Education degree were added to the curriculum in 1951. In 1953, the name \"'''Western Carolina College'''\" was adopted.\n\nIn 1967, the institution was designated a regional university by the [[North Carolina General Assembly]] and given its current title, \"'''Western Carolina University'''.\"<ref>{{cite web| title =Strategic Planning/Mission Statement 2004 | publisher =Western Carolina University|date=January 2004| url =http://www.wcu.edu/chancellor/Strategic%20Planning-Mission%20Statement%202004.htm}}</ref> On July 1, 1972, WCU became a member of the [[University of North Carolina]] system.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina University| publisher =University of North Carolina| date =September 13, 2007| url =http://intranet.northcarolina.edu/docs/assessment/Profiles/2007-08/WCU_Inst._Profile_07-08_38.pdf| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20081121003813/http://intranet.northcarolina.edu/docs/assessment/Profiles/2007-08/WCU_Inst._Profile_07-08_38.pdf| archivedate =November 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Precis of the university's history===\n{| cellpadding=4\n| '''Year''' || '''Name and Levels'''<ref>{{cite web| title =2006 Fact Book \u2013 Western Carolina University| publisher =University of North Carolina| date =November 10, 2006\n| url =http://www.wcu.edu/WebFiles/PDFs/OIPE_fboverview06.pdf}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1889 || Semi-private school\n|-\n| 1891 || Cullowhee High School\n|-\n| 1893 || First state appropriation; Normal Department established; First graduating class\n|-\n| 1905 || Cullowhee Normal and Industrial School\n|-\n| 1912 || Junior College rank established; Secondary school discontinued\n|-\n| 1913 || First college-level (one-year) degree awarded\n|-\n| 1925 || Cullowhee State Normal School\n|-\n| 1929 || Western Carolina Teachers College; Senior College rank established\n|-\n| 1931 || First Baccalaureate degree awarded\n|-\n| 1951 || Graduate degree established\n|-\n| 1952 || First master's degree awarded\n|-\n| 1953 || Western Carolina College\n|-\n| 1967 || Western Carolina University\n|-\n| 1972 || A constituent institution of the University of North Carolina\n|}\n\n==Facilities==\n===General location===\n[[File:Map of North Carolina highlighting Jackson County.svg|left|thumb|250px|Map of North Carolina highlighting Jackson County, NC]]\n\nWestern Carolina University is located in [[Jackson County, North Carolina|Jackson County]], in the [[unincorporated area|unincorporated]] village of [[Cullowhee, North Carolina]]. The university operates learning centers in both [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] and [[Cherokee, North Carolina|Cherokee]] with programs offered online and at various [[community colleges]].<ref>{{cite web| title =Programs in Biltmore Park| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6249.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =Cherokee Center| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6306.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =Community College and Community Center | publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/2814.asp}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| title =WCU, N.C. community colleges unveil comprehensive transfer | publisher =Western Carolina University| date =May 9, 2007 | url =http://www.wcu.edu/3242.asp}}</ref> The main campus is located in a valley of the [[Tuckasegee River]], between the [[Blue Ridge Mountains|Blue Ridge]] and [[Great Smoky Mountains]], {{convert|52|mi|km}} west of [[Asheville, North Carolina]] and 5 miles south of [[Sylva, NC]]. The university lies close to the [[Great Smoky Mountains National Park]], the [[Blue Ridge Parkway]], the Eastern Band of Cherokee Indians Reservation (officially known as the [[Qualla Boundary]]), and some of the nation's most beautiful [[United States National Forest|national forest]] lands. At an elevation of {{convert|2100|ft|m}}, but located in a thermal valley, the campus enjoys the best of all four seasons but is shielded from most extreme temperatures by surrounding peaks. Cullowhee typically enjoys a rather mild winter season. In fact, Cullowhee can go some winters with little to no snowfall.<ref>{{cite web| title =1971\u20132000 Climate Normals CULLOWHEE, NORTH CAROLINA (312200)| publisher =State Climate Office of North Carolina| year =2012| url =http://www.nc-climate.ncsu.edu/cronos/normals.php?station=312200| access-date =2012-08-23| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20130504064056/http://www.nc-climate.ncsu.edu/cronos/normals.php?station=312200| archive-date =2013-05-04| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\nWhile winters in the valley are generally mild, snow is not unusual in the higher elevations of Jackson County around [[Cashiers]] or [[Balsam, North Carolina|Balsam]]. In nearby Sapphire Valley, snowmaking machines maintain prime snow skiing conditions from mid-December through February. Locations in Jackson County are also within reasonable driving distance to ski slopes at [[Maggie Valley]]. The Blue Ridge Parkway is usually closed during winter weather, and has become popular with cross-country skiers during those times.<ref>{{cite web| title =A Photographic Journal of the Blue Ridge Parkway| publisher =Blue Ridge Parkway Guide| year =2008| url =http://www.virtualblueridge.com/photojournal/2004/01/31-001.asp}}</ref>\n\nThe many rivers, streams and forests surrounding Cullowhee, combined with the mild climate of Southern Appalachia, offer many opportunities for outdoor activities. Climbing, hiking, biking, rafting, kayaking, and camping are a few of the outdoor activities nearby.<ref>{{cite web| title =Outdoor Activities | publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/28442.asp}}</ref> Cities within a three-hour drive of campus include Atlanta, Georgia;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Atlanta&1s=GA&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Atlanta, GA to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> Charlotte, North Carolina;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Charlotte&1s=NC&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Charlotte, NC to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> Knoxville, Tennessee;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Knoxville&1s=TN&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Knoxville, TN to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> and Greenville, South Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mapquest.com/maps?1c=Greenville&1s=SC&2c=Cullowhee&2s=NC |title=Driving Directions from Greenville, SC to Cullowhee, NC |publisher=Mapquest.com |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref>\n\n===Main campus in Cullowhee===\n[[File:WCU 2007.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|WCU 2007|Western Carolina University in 2007]]\n\nThe main campus in Cullowhee offers most of the amenities of a small town, including fourteen residence halls,<ref name=ResHalls>{{cite web | title =Residence Halls | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/8141.asp | year =2012}}</ref> two full-service cafeterias, a food court with fast-food outlets, health services, counseling, a bookstore, [[Hunter Library|library]], an swimming pool, tennis courts, movie theater, jogging trail and quarter-mile track, hiking and biking trails and intramural fields.\n\nThe campus center is the A.K. Hinds University Center.<ref>{{cite web | title =A.K. Hinds University Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/171.asp | year =2012}}</ref>  The UC contains the university post office, a movie theater, video and commuter lounges, student organization HQs including the Student Government Association and Last Minute Productions, meeting rooms and office spaces.  Outside of the UC is the \"Alumni Tower\", built in 1989, on the 100th birthday of the university.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcu.edu/448.asp |title=Western Carolina University \u2013 Alumni Tower |publisher=Wcu.edu |date=October 28, 1989 |accessdate=2012-04-28}}</ref> Other newly constructed facilities include the Center for Applied Technology (which houses new engineering laboratories); an expanded student life center; new athletic facilities; and a new student support center.\n\nA $13.5 million {{convert|73000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} Student Recreation Center, was completed over the summer of 2008.<ref>{{cite web| title =Campus Recreation Center| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/7719.asp}}</ref> Harrill Residence Hall was renovated to add 6,000 square feet (557 m2) and bring the 1971 building to [[LEED standards]] of environmental friendliness and energy efficiency, and re-opened in fall 2012.\n\nThe new $46.2 million Health and Human Sciences Building opened for use at the start of the 2012\u201313 academic year, also built to LEED standards. This facility is the first project on the Millennial Initiative property and houses WCU's educational and outreach programs in the College of Health and Human Sciences. The four-story facility is home to the undergraduate and graduate programs in social work and communication sciences and disorders; graduate programs in physical therapy and health sciences; and undergraduate programs in athletic training, emergency medical care, environmental health, nutrition and dietetics, nursing and recreational therapy.<ref>{{cite web | title =Residence hall, new health building open for fall | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://news-prod.wcu.edu/2012/08/new-building-renovated-residence-hall-open/ | year=2012}}</ref>\n\n===Asheville campus===\nWCU's educational facilities in Asheville focus on professional and graduate degrees for working students.\n\n===Cherokee campus===\nThe Western Carolina University Cherokee Center in [[Cherokee, North Carolina]], was established in 1975 in cooperation with the tribal government of the Eastern Band of the Cherokee Indians.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina University Center in Cherokee| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2012| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6306.asp}}</ref> The center serves Cherokee and the surrounding communities and is available to all of the people of the region. Their services include the application process, transcript request, scholarships, internships placement, high school recruitment.\n\n==Organization and administration==\n[[File:Robert lee madison.jpg|left|150px|thumb|Robert Lee Madison, founder and first president]]\nThe university is led by Chancellor Kelli R. Brown, the chief administrative officer, along with Interim Provost and Vice Chancellor for Academic Affairs Richard Starnes and several advisory groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wcu.edu/335.asp |title=Western Carolina University \u2013 Office of the Chancellor |publisher=Wcu.edu |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wcu.edu/334.asp |title=Western Carolina University \u2013 Office of the Provost |publisher=Wcu.edu |accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref> The institution operates under the guidance and policies of the Board of Trustees of Western Carolina University.<ref>{{cite web | title =Board of Trustees | url =http://www.wcu.edu/23798.asp | year =2012}}</ref> WCU also falls under the administration of University of North Carolina system president [[Thomas W. Ross]].  The university moved to a provost and senior vice chancellor model in 2004.\n\n===University media===\nThe university produces the following publications and broadcasts:\n* ''Western Carolina Magazine]:''<ref>{{cite web | title =Western Carolina Magazine | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://magazine.wcu.edu  | year =2012}}</ref> A seasonal publication primarily for alumni and friends of WCU, Western Carolina Magazine contains features on university people and programs, alumni updates, and news and events.\n* ''Inside WCU'':<ref>{{cite web | title =The Reporter | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://thereporter.wcu.edu | year =2012}}</ref> A weekly electronic newsletter for the faculty and staff of WCU, The Reporter features news, events and campus community updates.\n* ''MountainRise:''<ref>{{cite web | title =MountainRise | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/facctr/mountainrise/ | year =2012}}</ref> An open, peer-reviewed, international electronic journal published twice a year by the Coulter Faculty Center for Excellence in Teaching & Learning at Western Carolina University for the purpose of being an international vehicle for the Scholarship of Teaching & Learning (SoTL).\n* ''All-Western Carolina:'' The ''All-Western Carolina'' radio program airs during half-time of Catamount Sports Network broadcasts and highlights WCU's academic all-stars and happenings on campus.\n\nWCU students, faculty and staff also contribute to:\n*''WCU on iTunes U''<ref>{{cite web | title =WCU on iTunes U | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://itunes.wcu.edu/ | year =2009 | access-date =2012-08-24 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120924094603/http://itunes.wcu.edu/ | archive-date =2012-09-24 | url-status =dead }}</ref> Faculty and students are podcasting using WCU on iTunes U service from [[Apple Inc]]. This media repository was publicly listed on the [[iTunes U]] Colleges and Universities listings in August 2009.\n\n==Academics and research==\n\n===Academic structure===\nWestern Carolina University\u2019s academic programs are housed in six colleges: Arts and Sciences, Business, Education and Allied Professions, Fine and Performing Arts, Health and Human Sciences, and Engineering and Technology. WCU also has an Honors College and Graduate School, and offers several interdisciplinary programs:<ref>{{cite web | title =Western Carolina University \u2013 Departments, Schools and Colleges | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/42.asp}}</ref>\n\n*College of Health and Human Sciences\n**Communication Sciences and Disorders\n**School of Health Sciences\n***Emergency Medical Care\n**School of Nursing\n**Physical Therapy\n**Social Work\n*College of Arts and Sciences\n**Anthropology and Sociology\n**Biology\n**Chemistry and Physics\n**Communication\n**Criminology and Criminal Justice\n**English\n**Geosciences and Natural Resources\n**History\n**Mathematics and Computer Science\n**World Languages\n**Philosophy and Religion\n**Political Science and Public Affairs\n*College of Fine and Performing Arts\n**Department of Stage and Screen\n**School of Art and Design\n**School of Music\n*College of Business\n**Accounting, Finance, Information Systems and Economics\n**Business Administration and Law and Sport Management\n**Entrepreneurship, Sales and Marketing, and Hospitality and Tourism\n***Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation\n***Center for Professional Selling and Marketing\n**Global Management and Strategy\n**Sales and Marketing\n***Center for Professional Selling and Marketing\n*College of Education and Allied Professions\n**School of Teaching and Learning\n**Human Services\n**Psychology\n*College of Engineering and Technology\n*The Kimmel School of Construction Management\n*The Honors College\n*The Graduate School\n*Interdisciplinary Programs: Science Education, Social Sciences Education, Environmental Sciences, Forensic Science, and International Studies, Integrated Health Sciences\n\n===Academic programs===\nWith its main campus located on the site of an ancient Cherokee Indian village<ref>{{cite web| title =Students Sift Through Centuries at Mound Site on Western Carolina's Campus| publisher =Western Carolina University| date =July 2, 2003| url =http://www.wcu.edu/pubinfo/news/mounddig.htm}}</ref> and adjacent to the Great Smoky and Blue Ridge Mountains, Western Carolina has a commitment to the rich traditions of both the [[Appalachia]]n and [[Cherokee]] cultures. The university's Mountain Heritage Center;<ref name=\"Mountain Heritage Center\">{{cite web | title =Mountain Heritage Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/2389.asp | year =2012}}</ref> Cherokee Center;<ref>{{cite web | title =Cherokee Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6306.asp | year =2012}}</ref> Craft Revival Project;<ref>{{cite web | title =Craft Revival Project | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/library/DigitalCollections/CraftRevival/index.htm | year =2012}}</ref> Cherokee Studies Program<ref>{{cite web | title =Cherokee Studies Program | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6302.asp | year =2012}}</ref> and WCU's partnership to preserve the Cherokee language<ref>{{cite web| title =Preserving the Cherokee Language| publisher =Western Carolina University| url =http://www.wcu.edu/298.asp | year =2012}}</ref> all reflect that influence \u2013 and provide educational resources for the region.<ref>{{cite web| title =University Awards and Accolades| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2009| url =http://www.wcu.edu/6620.asp}}</ref>\n\nWestern is [[Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education|classified]] among \"M1: Master's Colleges and Universities \u2013 Larger programs\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Western Carolina University |publisher=[[Indiana University]] |date=2020 |url=https://carnegieclassifications.iu.edu/lookup/view_institution.php?unit_id=200004}}</ref> and in the elective \"community engagement\" category.<ref>{{cite web| title =Carnegie Foundation recognizes WCU for community engagement | publisher =Western Carolina University| date =December 19, 2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/12218.asp}}</ref> WCU is accredited by the Commission on Colleges of the [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]] to award degrees at the bachelor, masters, intermediate, and doctoral levels. The university holds 21 program accreditations and is a member of more than 30 state and national associations and organizations to which its professional programs are related. In 2009, the Corporation for National and Community Service recognized WCU by awarding the President's Higher Education Community Service Honor Roll with Distinction for \"exemplary commitment to service and civic engagement\" on WCU's campus and beyond.<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU recognized with distinction on national honor roll for service| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2009| url =http://www.wcu.edu/12941.asp}}</ref>\n\nAs the sixth-largest producer of teachers in North Carolina, the College of Education and Allied Professions was the national winner of the Association of Teacher Educators' Distinguished Program in Teacher Education Award<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU Teacher Education Program is Recipient of National Award | publisher =Western Carolina University| date =February 24, 2006\n| url =http://www.wcu.edu/pubinfo/news/2006/CEAPnationalaward.htm}}</ref> in 2006.  The college is also the 2007 co-winner of the Christa McAuliffe Excellence in Teacher Education Award<ref>{{cite web| title =Teacher education program wins national Christa McAuliffe Award| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/5183.asp}}</ref> presented by the American Association of State Colleges and Universities. The Christa McAuliffe Award nationally recognizes outstanding programs in teacher education at AASCU member institutions.\n\nWestern Carolina's Forensic Research Facility (commonly referred to as the \"FoREST\") is just the second facility of its kind nationally.<ref>{{cite web| title =Forensic Research Facility| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/293.asp}}</ref> The decomposition research station is an extremely valuable resource for researchers and forensic anthropology students to study natural decomposition.\n\nThe residential Honors College was first of its kind in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web| title =Only at WCU| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/28.asp}}</ref> Newly accepted students are invited to live in one of two exclusive residence halls on campus. The Honors College is one of a few in the state to offer a residential option and among a few nationwide to award graduates with a special honors diploma. The college began in 1998 with 77 students and has grown to approximately 1,400. For entering freshman, the Honor's College average weighted GPA is over 4.00 and the average SAT score is 1380.  The College is a member of the National Collegiate Honors Council.<ref>{{cite web | title =Member Institutions \u2013 National Collegiate Honors Council | publisher =National Collegiate Honors Council | url =http://nchchonors.org/members-area/member-institutions-4/ | year =2012 | access-date =2012-08-23 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20120902224619/http://nchchonors.org/members-area/member-institutions-4/ | archive-date =2012-09-02 | url-status =dead }}</ref>  In August 2009, Balsam Hall, the first part of a $50.2 million Honors College residential community located at the center of campus opened, housing 426 students. In Fall 2010, Blue Ridge Hall completed the community and add an additional 400 beds for Honors College students and Teaching Fellows.<ref>{{cite web| title =Balsam Hall opens to first 298 residents| publisher =the Reporter| year =2009| url =http://thereporter.wcu.edu/2009/08/new-residence-hall-opens-to-first-298-students/}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 2000, WCU was officially designated a [[National Merit]] sponsoring university, just the fourth institution of higher education in North Carolina, public or private, to receive that distinction<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU Becomes 4TH National Merit Sponsor Among N.C. Universities| publisher =Western Carolina University| date =April 12, 2000| url =http://www.wcu.edu/pubinfo/news/merit.html}}</ref>  The university grants scholarships to students who qualify as National Merit Finalists. The Western Meritorious Award for Finalists provides a four-year scholarship, which covers the equivalent amount of in-state tuition, fees, room, and board, to National Merit Finalists, who also receive a computer.\n\nThe 2012 edition of the U.S. News & World Report guide to \"America's Best Colleges\" ranks Western Carolina University 14th<ref>{{cite web| title =U.S. News and World Report Best Colleges 2012| publisher =U.S. News and World Report| date =August 2012| url =http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/rankings/regional-universities-south/top-public}}</ref>  among public universities in the South that offer master's degrees.\n\nIn 2015, the [[North Carolina General Assembly]] approved the the NC Promise Tuition Plan, a tuition reduction plan to make three universities  - WCU, [[Elizabeth City State University]], and [[University of North Carolina at Pembroke]] - more affordable and accessible. The NC Promise began in the fall semester of 2018 and drastically reduces the tuition cost for students. In-state students pay $500 a semester and out-of-state students pay $2,500 a semester.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northcarolina.edu/Prospective-Students/NC-Promise|title=NC Promise {{!}} UNC System Office|website=www.northcarolina.edu|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> Attendance has increased for three consecutive years with the total attendance as of Fall 2019 at 12,167 students (10,469 undergraduate and 1,698 graduate students).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wcu.edu/discover/about/fast-facts.aspx|title=Western Carolina University|website=Fast Facts|language=en|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\n===Centers, institutes, and affiliates===\nCommunity focus, scholarly research, business development, preservation of the Cherokee & Appalachian Mountain cultures, and the advancement of technology & public policy are the guiding foci of Western Carolina's Centers, Institutes & Affiliates.<ref>{{cite web | title =Centers, Institutes and Affiliates | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/223.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n\n<div style=\"float:left; width:40%;\">\n*Center for Rapid Product Realization<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for Rapid Product Realization | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/3632.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n**Carolinas MicroOptics Triangle\n**Carolinas Photonics Consortium\n*Center for Study of Free Enterprise \n*Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for Entrepreneurship and Innovation | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/3857.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center of Professional Selling and Marketing<ref>{{cite web | title =Center of Professional Selling and Marketing | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/12975.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center for Math/Science Education<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for Math/Science Education | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6087.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Cherokee Studies<ref>{{cite web | title =Cherokee Studies | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/6302.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n**Projects and Initiatives from Cherokee Studies\n**Cherokee Studies Academic Programs\n**Cherokee Center\n**Revitalization of Traditional Cherokee Artisan Resources\n*John W. Bardo Fine & Performing Arts Center<ref>{{cite web | title =John W. Bardo Fine and Performing Arts Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/bardoartscenter/index.html | year =2012}}</ref>\n\n</div><div style=\"float:right; width:50%;\">\n*Center for the Support of Beginning Teachers<ref>{{cite web | title =Center for the Support of Beginning Teachers | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/7585.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Mountain Heritage Center<ref name=\"Mountain Heritage Center\"/>\n*The Public Policy Institute<ref>{{cite web | title =The Public Policy Institute | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/9355.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Ramsey Regional Activities Center<ref>{{cite web | title=Ramsey Regional Activities Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url=http://ramsey.wcu.edu/ | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Small Business & Technology Development Center<ref>{{cite web | title =Small Business & Technology Development Center | publisher =University of North Carolina system | url =http://www.sbtdc.org/ | year =2012}}</ref> partner\n*Writing and Learning Commons<ref>{{cite web | title=Writing and Learning Commons | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/29229.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Program for the Study of Developed Shorelines<ref>{{cite web | title =Program for the Study of Developed Shorelines | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/1037.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Speech and Hearing Clinic<ref>{{cite web | title =Speech and Hearing Clinic | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/8393.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Myron L. Coulter Faculty Commons for Excellence in Teaching and Learning<ref>{{cite web | title =Coulter Faculty Commons | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/7072.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Southern Appalachian Biodiversity and Ecology Center<ref>{{cite web | title =Southern Appalachian Biodiversity and Ecology Center | publisher =Western Carolina University | url=http://www.wcu.edu/7401.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Center for Service Learning and Community Engagement<ref>{{cite web | title=Center for Service Learning | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/9815.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n*Local Government Training Program<ref>{{cite web | title =Local Government Training Program | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/10147.asp |year =2012}}</ref>\n*Mountain Area Pro Bono Health Care\n</div>{{Clear}}\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Residential life===\nThe main campus at Cullowhee has residential facilities for students. These include thirteen residence halls,<ref name=ResHalls /> two full-service cafeterias, and one food court with fast-food outlets. The halls house more than 4,500 WCU students each academic year.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wcu.edu/discover/about/fast-facts.aspx | title = Fast Facts | work = About Western Carolina University | publisher = Western Carolina University | date = | access-date = May 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe campus residence buildings include one for graduate students and one for married students. Special residence accommodations include honors residence halls and The Village, home to residential Greek and student organizations. Three new residence facilities were recently completed from a $50.2 million residence hall project. The two newest residence halls on campus are Balsam Residence Hall and Blue Ridge Residence Hall.<ref>{{cite web| title =Ground-breaking ceremony held for $50.2 million residence hall project| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2008| url =http://www.wcu.edu/7184.asp}}</ref> The $18 million {{convert|53000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} campus dining facility was opened in stages beginning in July 2009.<ref>{{cite web| title =WCU Prepares for 1,600 students at Freshman Move-in Day| publisher =Western Carolina University| year =2009| url =http://www.wcu.edu/24854.asp}}</ref>\n\n===Athletics===\n{{Main|Western Carolina Catamounts}}\n[[File:Ramsey Regional Activity Center in Cullowhee, NC.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Ramsey Center basketball and volleyball arena]]\n\nAs a member of the [[Southern Conference]], Western Carolina University participates in [[National Collegiate Athletics Association|NCAA]] [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] athletics.  Intercollegiate athletics include football, men and women's basketball, baseball, softball, women's soccer, men and women's golf, men and women's track and field (Indoor and Outdoor), cross country running, women's volleyball and tennis. Catamount football is a member of [[Division I FCS]] and plays at Whitmire Stadium. The Ramsey Center is home to men's and women's basketball, and women's volleyball. Baseball is played at Hennon Stadium, softball is played at the Catamount Softball Complex, and the Catamount Athletic Complex is home to women's soccer, tennis, and track and field.\n\nOn November 29, 1980, Western Carolina's Ronnie Carr made the first intercollegiate three-point field goal, in a game against [[Middle Tennessee State University]], a game WCU won 77\u201370.<ref>{{cite web| title =Three-point era got its start with Ronnie Carr| publisher =Rivals.com| date =May 21, 2007| url =http://collegebasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=675171| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20120309172943/http://collegebasketball.rivals.com/content.asp?cid=675171| archivedate =March 9, 2012}}</ref> The ball he used is on display at the [[Basketball Hall of Fame]] in Springfield, Massachusetts.\n\nWestern Carolina and [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] have a football rivalry in which they once competed in the [[Battle for the Old Mountain Jug]] on an annual basis.<ref>{{cite web| title =Western Carolina Announces 2008 Schedule| publisher =College Sporting News| year =2008| url =http://www.collegesportingnews.com/article.asp?articleid=89747}}</ref> The Catamounts football team was runner-up in the [[Division I-AA]] National Football Championship Game in 1983.<ref>{{cite web | title =1983\u201384 FCS Championship | url =http://www.fanbase.com/128297-1983-12-17 | archive-url =https://archive.today/20130122204602/http://www.fanbase.com/128297-1983-12-17 | url-status =dead | archive-date =2013-01-22 | year =2011 }}</ref>\n\nCurrent NCAA sports at WCU include:\n* Men - Baseball, Basketball, Cross Country, Football, Golf, Track and Field\n* Women - Basketball, Cross Country, Golf, Soccer, Softball, Tennis, Track and Field, Volleyball\n\nIn addition to NCAA athletics, Western Carolina University is also home to many different club sports, intramurals, and a dance team, including the following:\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Aquatics (Swimming)\n* Ballroom Dance\n* Dance (Jazz)<ref name=\"dance\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZJ9ETLRBYcY https://www.youtube.com] 2015-2016 Western Carolina University Dance Team: Road to Nationals.</ref>\n* Disc Golf\n* Equestrian\n* Fencing\n* Kendo\n* Men's Soccer\n* Men's Rugby\n* Men's Lacrosse\n* Mountain Biking\n* Ultimate Frisbee\n* Women's Lacrosse\n* Women's Rugby\n* Women's Volleyball\n* Wrestling\n{{div col end}}\n\nIn 2016 the WCU dance team won third place at the [[National Dance Alliance|NDA Nationals dance competition]], performing in [[Daytona Beach, Florida]].<ref name=\"dance\"/><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TyAFizag9ls https://www.youtube.com] WCU Dance Team - NDA 2016 - Daytona Beach.</ref>\n\n===Music===\n\n====Concerts and recitals====\nThe Schools of Music and Fine and Performing Arts offer a variety of events featuring students, faculty, and outside performers. These cultural opportunities are typically relatively cheap, and students can often attend them free of charge.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20150227170530/http://www.wcu.edu/academics/departments-schools-colleges/FPA/schools-departments-and-centers/music/prospective-music-students/music-ensembles/]</ref>\n\n====Pride of the Mountains====\n{{Main|Western Carolina University Pride of the Mountains Marching Band}}\n\nThe Pride of the Mountains is the largest college marching band in the Carolinas and Tennessee. As of Fall 2014, the marching band includes just over 500 members, making it one of the largest marching bands in the United States.  The band is open to all Western Carolina students regardless of class or major, with approximately 60% of its members non-music majors.\n\nIn 2014, the band performed in the [[Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade]] with 510 band members participating. Announcers described their performance as \"This is the largest band this parade has seen in decades\", \"This is the best of the best\", and \"They don't mess around at Western Carolina\".<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fuszup1CQfc https://www.youtube.com] Western Carolina University at Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade (2014).</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F_slJVRp41g https://www.youtube.com] Pride of the Mountains Marching Band at Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Pride of the Mountains to participate in Macy's Thanksgiving Day Parade | publisher =Western Carolina University | url = http://news-prod.wcu.edu/2013/04/pride-of-the-mountains-to-participate-in-2014-macys-thanksgiving-parade/ | year=2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Pride of the Mountains also performed at a [[Carolina Panthers]] halftime show in 2011.<ref>{{cite web | title=SLIDESHOW: Band marches at NFL game | publisher =Western Carolina University The Reporter | url = http://thereporter.wcu.edu/2011/09/slideshow-band-marches-at-nfl-game/ | year=2011}}</ref> The band was also the special guest at the [[Bands of America]] Grand National Championships in Indianapolis in 1998, 2003, 2008 and 2012, an honor given to only one college band in the United States each year. In addition, the band was also a special guest at the [[Bands of America]] Regional's held in Atlanta in 1995, 2006, 2010, and 2011.  In 2009, the Pride of the Mountains was selected as one of the five best collegiate marching bands in the nation by the College Band Directors National Association and featured in the book \"Marching Bands and Drumlines: Secrets of Success from the Best of the Best\" by Paul Buyer.\n\nThe band is the 2009 recipient of the [[Sudler Trophy]] awarded by the [[John Philip Sousa Foundation]].<ref name=\"CTHeisman\">{{cite web| title =WCU band wins 'Heisman' of marching bands| publisher =The Asheville Citizen-Time| year =2009| url =http://www.citizen-times.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090528/MOUNTAINNEWS/905280318}}</ref> They participated in the 2011 Tournament of Roses Parade in Pasadena, California, and won the most votes in a \"best band\" in the parade poll hosted by KTLA-TV.<ref>{{cite web | title =The Pride wins favorite band poll, returns home | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://roseparade.wcu.edu/the-pride-wins-favorite-band-poll-returns-home/ | year =2011}}</ref>\n\n===Greek life===\nWCU is home to a wide range of Greek [[fraternities]] and [[sororities]], as well as several councils and societies.<ref>{{cite web | title =Greek Life at WCU | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/12520.asp | year =2012}}</ref> The Greek community offers many social opportunities to enrich college life. Greeks get personal guidance in planning their curriculum and choosing classes and instructors, and assistance with registration and financial aid. Chapter study sessions, educational programs, tutoring, and study partners and teams offer support for developing and maintaining [[study skills]]. Greeks are recognized for their academic successes through Greek scholarship and awards programs and honor societies such as the Order of Omega. According to 2011\u201312 figures from ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'', 3.4% of WCU's male undergraduate students are in fraternities, while 3.6% of female undergraduate students are in sororities.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web| title =America's Best Colleges 2008: Western Carolina University: At a glance| publisher =usnews.com | year =2012| url =http://colleges.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-colleges/western-carolina-university-2981}}</ref>\n\n{|\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''Sororities'''\n*College Panhellenic Council (CPC)\n**[[Alpha Chi Omega]]\n**[[Alpha Gamma Delta]]\n**[[Alpha Xi Delta]]\n**[[Delta Zeta]]\n**[[Phi Mu]]\n**[[Kappa Delta]] (inactive)\n**[[Sigma Kappa]] (inactive)\n**[[Zeta Tau Alpha]] (inactive)\n\n'''Greek Councils & Societies'''\n*IFC\n*CPC\n*NPHC\n*[[Order of Omega]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''Fraternities'''\n*[[North American Interfraternity Conference]] (IFC)\n**[[Delta Sigma Phi]]\n**[[Kappa Alpha Order]]\n**[[Lambda Chi Alpha]]\n**[[Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia]] \n**[[Pi Kappa Phi]]\n**[[Pi Lambda Phi]]\n**[[Sigma Alpha Epsilon]]\n**[[Sigma Chi]]\n**[[Theta Xi]]\n**[[Alpha Sigma Phi]] (colony)\n**[[Delta Chi]] (inactive)\n**[[Kappa Sigma]] (inactive)\n**[[Pi Kappa Alpha]] (inactive)\n**[[Sigma Nu]] (inactive)\n**[[Sigma Phi Epsilon]] (inactive)\n**[[Tau Kappa Epsilon]] (inactive)\n| valign=\"top\" |\n'''Historically Black Fraternities'''\n*[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC)\n**[[Alpha Phi Alpha]]\n**[[Omega Psi Phi]]\n**[[Phi Beta Sigma]]\n**[[Kappa Alpha Psi]]\n**[[Phi Beta Sigma]] (inactive)\n'''Historically Black Sororities'''\n*[[National Pan-Hellenic Council]] (NPHC)\n**[[Alpha Kappa Alpha]]\n**[[Zeta Phi Beta]]\n**[[Delta Sigma Theta]] (inactive)\n\n'''[[Professional Fraternity Association]]'''\n*[[Phi Sigma Pi]] National Co-Ed Honors Fraternity<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://professionalfraternity.org/fraternal-members |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-01-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123115441/http://professionalfraternity.org/fraternal-members |archive-date=2016-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n'''No Council Affiliation'''\n*[[Sigma Alpha Omega]] (fraternity)\n*[[Epsilon Tau Pi]] (fraternity)\n*[[Alpha Pi Omega]] (sorority)\n|}\n\n===WCU student media===\nHoused in the Student Media Center (Old Student Union) on the hill area of campus are WCU's Student Media Organizations, which are open to all students and are produced by students.<ref>{{cite web | title =Student Media | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/108.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\nThe following organizations are a part of WCU Student Media:\n*'''WWCU-FM:''' [[WWCU]]-FM, Power 90.5, is the broadcast service of WCU and broadcasts 24 hours a day, 7 days a week as Jackson County's only FM radio station.\n* '''WCAT:''' Cable & Internet radio station offering an eclectic mix of music chosen by student DJs, as well as original talk shows and artist interviews. It broadcasts on the campus closed-circuit television station 22.\n* '''TV 62:''' The student-run campus television station, offering original programing to the campus on channel 62. It is WCU's closed-circuit television station with offices located in the A.K. Hinds University Center, an organization offering original programming that allows students to showcase their short films, as well as announce events on campus and highlight recent sporting events.\n* '''''The Nomad:''''' WCU's Literature & Art magazine, published once a year in the Spring semester. Student staff members work together to produce and distribute WCU's student literary magazine.\n* '''''The Gadfly:''''' WCU's Journal of Social Criticism and Philosophy. Satirical pieces philosophically critiquing society-at-large in a humorous manner. Published once a semester.<ref>{{cite web | title =The Gadfly | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/11994.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n* '''''Western Carolinian Newspaper:''''' A bi-weekly newspaper focusing on news and events relevant to the campus and surrounding community. Includes News, Features, Sports, and Arts & Entertainment sections. Available in print in the local area and on-line at www.westerncarolinian.com.<ref>{{cite web | title =Western Carolinian | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.westerncarolinian.com/ | year =2012}}</ref>\n* '''''The Western Carolina Journalist:''''' An online newspaper ran by the Communication department covering news about WCU and the surrounding areas<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewesterncarolinajournalist.com/ |title=The Western Carolina Journalist |publisher=Thewesterncarolinajournalist.com |date=2014-05-31 |accessdate=2014-08-24}}</ref>\n*'''''The Tuckasegee Valley Historical Review''''': The Tuckasegee Valley Historical Review is an annually published graduate history journal. The review publishes articles by WCU graduate students in history with a primarily local focus.<ref>{{cite web | title =Tuckasegee Valley Historical Review | publisher =Western Carolina University | url =http://www.wcu.edu/8152.asp | year =2012}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n===Alumni===\n\n*[[Gerald Austin]] \u2013 [[National Football League|NFL]] referee\n*[[Bobbi Baker]] \u2013 actress, best known for her role as Kiki on the Tyler Perry sitcom ''[[House of Payne]]''\n*[[James A. Beaty, Jr.]] \u2013 current U.S. District Judge and former nominee to the [[U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit]]\n*[[Dean Biasucci]] \u2013 athlete (former placekicker, NFL [[Indianapolis Colts]]), actor\n*[[Linda L. Bray]] \u2013 first female in the military to lead troops into combat\n*[[Sean Bridgers]] \u2013 actor, writer, director, producer\n*[[Andrew C. Brock]] \u2013 [[North Carolina Senate|North Carolina State Senator]]\n*[[Jared Burton]] \u2013 retired [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] [[pitcher]]<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/burtoja01.shtml|title= Jared Burton|publisher= Baseball-Reference.Com|accessdate= October 3, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Keion Crossen]] - cornerback, [[Houston Texans]]\n*[[Geoff Collins (American football)|Geoff Collins]] - head football coach at [[Georgia Tech]]\n*[[Ariana DeBose]] \u2013 actress, singer, and dancer\n*[[Louis Ducruet]]- scout at [[AS Monaco FC]], 12th in line to the Monagesque throne, grandson to Rainier III, Prince of Monaco and American actress Grace Kelly\n*[[Carol Fowler Durham]] \u2013 professor of Nursing at [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], interprofessional teams expert\n*[[Joe Firstman]] \u2013 musician and musical director\n*[[Ernest A. Fitzgerald]] (1947) \u2013 bishop of the [[United Methodist Church]]\n*[[Judy Green (volleyball coach)|Judy Green]] \u2013 head volleyball coach for the [[University of Alabama]]\n*[[Mel Gibson (basketball)|Mel Gibson]] \u2013 former basketball player for the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n*[[Rich Hall]] \u2013 comedian, writer\n*[[Greg Holland (baseball)|Greg Holland]] \u2013 MLB pitcher and MLB All-Star\n*[[Brad Hoover]] \u2013 former fullback for the NFL [[Carolina Panthers]]\n*[[Frank Huguelet]] \u2013 retired professional wrestler (as \"'Heavy Metal' Ric Savage'\"), television host\n*[[Sarah Hutchings]] \u2013 Composer\n*[[Paul Johnson (American football coach)|Paul Johnson]] \u2013 head football coach at [[Georgia Tech]]\n*[[Jeanne Jolly]] \u2013 singer, songwriter\n*[[Tony Jones (football player)|Tony Jones]] \u2013 football player with the NFL [[Denver Broncos]]\n*[[Andrew Jordan (football player)|Andrew Jordan]] \u2013 [[tight end]] in the NFL\n*[[David Joy (author)|David Joy]] \u2013 author\n*[[Keith LeClair]] \u2013 athlete and baseball coach at Western Carolina University\n*[[Henry Logan (basketball)|Henry Logan]] \u2013 athlete; in 1964 became North Carolina's first African-American collegiate athlete, and the first to play basketball for a \"white\" public institution in 1964\n*[[Kevin Martin (basketball, born 1983)|Kevin Martin]] \u2013 professional basketball player<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/martike02.html|title = Kevin Martin|publisher= Basketball=Reference.com|accessdate= December 21, 2012}}</ref>\n*[[Manteo Mitchell]] \u2013 track and field athlete, 2012 London Olympic medalist\n*[[Percy Watson|Nick McNeil]] \u2013 former NFL player, [[WWE]] professional wrestler (as '\"Showtime!' Percy Watson\")\n*[[Mary Cordell Nesbitt]] \u2013 politician\n*[[David Patten]] \u2013 NFL wide receiver\n*[[Dave Pember]] \u2013 former pitcher for MLB [[Milwaukee Brewers]]\n*[[J. T. Poston]] - [[professional golfer]]\n*[[Rachel Reilly (Big Brother)|Rachel Reilly]] \u2013 reality television show contestant, television host\n*[[David Sedaris]] \u2013 humorist, comedian, author, and radio contributor\n*[[Geno Segers]] \u2013 former professional rugby player, actor.\n*[[Clyde Simmons]] \u2013 defensive end for the NFL [[Philadelphia Eagles]]\n*[[Tim Sinicki]] \u2013 head baseball coach at intercollegiate [[Binghamton Bearcats baseball|Binghamton]]<ref name=sinicki>{{cite news|last1=Mangan|first1=Mike|title=Five Questions: Binghamton University's Tim Sinicki|url=http://www.pressconnects.com/article/20140603/SPORTS03/306030015/Five-Questions-Binghamton-University-s-Tim-Sinicki|accessdate=June 28, 2014|work=PressConnects.com|publisher=Press & Sun-Bulletin|date=June 3, 2014|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6QfYd0g5u?url=http://www.pressconnects.com/article/20140603/SPORTS03/306030015/Five-Questions-Binghamton-University-s-Tim-Sinicki?nclick_check=1|archivedate=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Matt Stillwell]] \u2013 Nashville recording artist\n*[[Wayne Tolleson]] \u2013 [[Major League Baseball]] player 1981-1990\n*[[Willie Williams (American football)|Willie Williams]] \u2013 NFL defensive back for [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n\n===Faculty===\n*[[Robert J. Conley]] \u2013 award-winning author\n*[[Terrance Mann]] \u2013 stage actor, director, singer, songwriter, and dancer\n*[[Ron Rash]] \u2013 award-winning author\n*[[Laura Wright (academic)|Laura Wright]] \u2013 founder of academic field of [[vegan studies]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.wcu.edu}}\n*[http://www.catamountsports.com Western Carolina Athletics website]\n\n{{Western Carolina University}}\n{{University of North Carolina}}\n{{Southern Conference navbox}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1889]]\n[[Category:Education in Jackson County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges accredited by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Western Carolina University]]\n[[Category:Education in Asheville, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Educati